content:
We shipped a Vite + React single page app with about 280 routes: marketing pages, a blog, and a batch of programmatically generated county pages. All client rendered. The problem is not users, it is crawlers and share cards. A raw SPA serves the same index.html for every route, so anything that does not execute JavaScript sees an identical, empty shell no matter which URL it requested. This post walks through the actual prerender pipeline we run after every build, what it gets right, what it does not, and the two gotchas that cost us the most time. The site is virdix.co if you want to see the output in practice.

Why we did not just switch to a meta framework

The obvious answer is "use Next.js" or "use Remix." We did not, for a boring reason: the app was already a mature Vite SPA with its own routing (wouter), its own build pipeline, and no server. Rewriting the framework to get SSR would have meant rewriting the app. What we actually needed was much narrower: crawlers and social scrapers need to see the right title, meta description, Open Graph tags, and JSON-LD for each URL. Real users, who run JavaScript, do not need any of that baked in, they get it from a React effect the moment the page mounts.

So the fix is a post-build script, not a framework migration.

The pipeline

After vite build produces dist/, a Node script does the following:

• Spins up a tiny local HTTP server that serves dist/ as static files, falling back to the built index.html shell for any path that is not a real file (the same behavior the production host needs to provide for client side routing to work).

• Launches headless Chromium via Puppeteer.

• For every route in a list, opens a new page, navigates to it, and waits for two things: the app's root element to have children, and document.title to be non empty. That second check matters more than it sounds like it should.

• Serializes document.documentElement.outerHTML and writes it to dist/<route>/index.html (or dist/index.html for the homepage, dist/404.html for the not found route).

The route list itself is generated, not hand maintained. Static marketing routes live in an array, but blog slugs and county page slugs are discovered by reading the actual data files in the repo (readdirSync over the county data directory, a regex over blog post metadata) so the prerender list can never silently drift out of sync with what the app actually renders.

Why "wait for title" instead of a fixed timeout

Early versions of this script used a flat waitForTimeout(2000) after navigation. It worked until it did not: on a slower CI runner, some pages had not finished mounting by the 2 second mark, so we wrote empty shells to disk for a handful of routes and did not notice until a Search Console coverage report flagged pages with no content.

The fix was to wait on an actual signal instead of a guess:

await page.waitForFunction(
() => {
const el = document.querySelector("#root");
return el && el.children.length > 0 && document.title.length > 0;
},
{ timeout: 45000 },
);

